'''Takeda Shrine''' has an but it is said to have been founded by the {{ill|Yūki no Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|結城国造|12=draft}} lineage of the {{ill|Takeda no Omi|ja|竹田臣|12=draft}}, who enshrined their ancestor, Takenuokawa Wake no Mikoto. This deity was one of the {{ill|Shidō Shōgun|ja|四道将軍|12=draft}}, a group of four generals dispatched to pacify and develop the eastern provinces. The shrine is recorded in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyocho|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|12=draft}} under "Takeda Shrine of Yūki District, Shimōsa Province," making it one of the 11 shrines listed for Shimōsa Province. In 1764 (Hōreki 14), the shrine was relocated to the grounds of {{ill|Jōkoku-ji|ja|乗国寺|12=draft}}, a {{ill|Sōtō Zen|ja|曹洞宗|12=draft}} temple that serves as the ancestral temple of the {{ill|Yūki clan|ja|結城氏|12=draft}}.

'''Suga Shrine''' was established in 1242 (Ninji 3) when the ruling {{ill|Yūki clan|ja|結城氏|12=draft}} invited the deity from {{ill|Tsushima Shrine|ja|津島神社|12=draft}} in {{ill|Owari Province|ja|尾張国|12=draft}}, naming it '''Tenno-sha''' (天王社). In 1343 (Kōei 2), {{ill|Yūki Naoasa|ja|結城直朝|12=draft}} designated it as one of the '''Yūki Seven Shrines''' (結城七社) and made it the {{ill|Sōja|ja|総社|12=draft}} (main provincial shrine) of {{ill|Yūki District|ja|結城郷|12=draft}}. During the {{ill|Shinbutsu Bunri|ja|神仏分離|12=draft}} reforms in 1868 (Meiji 1), the shrine was renamed '''Suga Shrine'''. 

In 1870 (Meiji 3), Takeda Shrine was separated from Jōkoku-ji and merged with Suga Shrine, forming '''Takeda Suga Shrine'''. In 1873 (Meiji 6), the shrine was designated as a {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|12=draft}}, and in 1930 (Shōwa 5), it was elevated to a {{ill|Prefectural Shrine|ja|県社|12=draft}}.

