'''Takeda Suga Shrine''' (健田須賀神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in {{ill|Yūki, Ibaraki|ja|結城市|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yūki, Ibaraki|qq=}}, Japan. The shrine is classified as a former Prefectural Shrine and was formed in the Meiji period by merging the {{ill|Takeda Shrine|ja|健田神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeda Shrine|qq=}} and {{ill|Suga Shrine|ja|須賀神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suga Shrine|qq=}}, with the former being a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|qq=draft|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|qq=}}.

The shrine enshrines {{ill|Takenouchi no Sukune|ja|武渟川別命|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takenouchi no Sukune|qq=}}, the deity of the original Takeda Shrine, and {{ill|Susanoo|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|須佐之男命|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=}}, the deity of the original Suga Shrine.

== History ==
The '''Takeda Shrine''' has an unclear founding date but is said to have been established by the Yūki Province {{ill|Yūki clan|ja|結城国造|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yūki clan|qq=}}, who enshrined their ancestral deity {{ill|Takenouchi no Sukune|ja|武渟川別命|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takenouchi no Sukune|qq=}}. Takenouchi no Sukune was one of the {{ill|Shido Shōgun|ja|四道将軍|1=Shidō Shōgun|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shido Shōgun|13=User:Immanuelle/Shidō Shōgun|qq=}}, credited with pacifying and developing eastern Japan. The shrine is listed in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Jinmyōchō|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Jinmyōchō|qq=}} as "Kenda Shrine" under the 11 shrines of {{ill|Shimousa Province|ja|下総国|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimousa Province|qq=}}. In 1764 (Hōreki 14), the shrine was relocated to the grounds of {{ill|Jōkoku-ji|ja|乗国寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōkoku-ji|qq=}}, a {{ill|Sōtō Zen|ja|曹洞宗|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sōtō Zen|qq=}} temple.

The '''Suga Shrine''' was established in 1242 (Ninji 3) by the {{ill|Yūki clan|ja|結城氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yūki clan|qq=}}, who brought its deity from the {{ill|Tsushima Shrine|ja|津島神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsushima Shrine|qq=}} in Owari Province. Initially called "Tennōsha," it became the collective shrine for Yūki district in 1343 (Kōei 2) under the Yūki clan. During the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離令|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu bunri|qq=}} of the Meiji period, the name was changed from Tennōsha to Suga Shrine.

In 1870 (Meiji 3), the Takeda Shrine separated from Jōkoku-ji and was merged with the Suga Shrine to form the '''Takeda Suga Shrine'''. It was Ranked as a {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gōsha|qq=}} in 1873 (Meiji 6) and elevated to a Prefectural Shrine in 1930 (Shōwa 5).

