'''Takeda Suga Shrine''' (健田須賀神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|qid=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|Yūki, Ibaraki|en|Yūki, Ibaraki|qid=Q847569|lt=Yūki, Ibaraki|1=Yūki, Ibaraki}}, Japan. The shrine is classified as a former Prefectural Shrine and was formed in the Meiji period by merging the {{ill|Takeda Shrine|ja|健田神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeda Shrine|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 健田須賀神社}} and {{ill|Suga Shrine|ja|須賀神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suga Shrine|qq=}}, with the former being a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|13=User:Immanuelle|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|lt=Shikinaisha}}.

The shrine enshrines {{ill|Takenouchi no Sukune|ja|武渟川別命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takenouchi no Sukune|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 武渟川別}}, the deity of the original Takeda Shrine, and {{ill|Susanoo|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|須佐之男命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to スサノオ}}, the deity of the original Suga Shrine.

== History ==
The '''Takeda Shrine''' has an unclear founding date but is said to have been established by the Yūki Province {{ill|Yūki clan|ja|結城国造|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yūki clan|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, who enshrined their ancestral deity {{ill|Takenouchi no Sukune|ja|武渟川別命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takenouchi no Sukune|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 武渟川別}}. Takenouchi no Sukune was one of the {{ill|Shido Shōgun|ja|四道将軍|1=Shidō Shōgun|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shido Shōgun|13=User:Immanuelle/Shidō Shōgun|qq=}}, credited with pacifying and developing eastern Japan. The shrine is listed in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Jinmyōchō|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Jinmyōchō|qq=}} as "Kenda Shrine" under the 11 shrines of {{ill|Shimōsa Province|en|Shimōsa Province|qid=Q1053695|lt=Shimousa Province|1=Shimōsa Province}}. In 1764 (Hōreki 14), the shrine was relocated to the grounds of {{ill|Jōkoku-ji|ja|乗国寺|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōkoku-ji|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, a {{ill|Sōtō|en|Sōtō|qid=Q749085|lt=Sōtō Zen|1=Sōtō}} temple.

The '''Suga Shrine''' was established in 1242 (Ninji 3) by the {{ill|Yūki clan|en|Yūki clan|qid=Q2975399|lt=Yūki clan|1=Yūki clan}}, who brought its deity from the {{ill|Tsushima Shrine|en|Tsushima Shrine|qid=Q705136|lt=Tsushima Shrine|1=Tsushima Shrine}} in Owari Province. Initially called "Tennōsha," it became the collective shrine for Yūki district in 1343 (Kōei 2) under the Yūki clan. During the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離令|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu bunri|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 神仏分離}} of the Meiji period, the name was changed from Tennōsha to Suga Shrine.

In 1870 (Meiji 3), the Takeda Shrine separated from Jōkoku-ji and was merged with the Suga Shrine to form the '''Takeda Suga Shrine'''. It was Ranked as a {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|1=Gō-sha|qid=Q134917316}}{{efn|District Shrines|qid=Q90139226|lt=Ken-sha|1=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gōsha|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 近代社格制度|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q712534}} in 1873 (Meiji 6) and elevated to a Prefectural Shrine in 1930 (Shōwa 5).

